atus>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G0400959</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The genetic material (DNA) is continuously broken and attacked by reactive molecules and during normal cellular activities. The commonest lesions arising in cells are chromosomal DNA single-strand breaks, in which one strand of the DNA double helix is broken. This work will address the hypothesis that the cellular machinery that repairs chromosomal single-strand breaks is important for maintaining proper function of the nervous system. It will address the possibility that defects in this machinery result in hereditary, debilitating, and progressive neurological disease. This work may also identify the molecular abnormality present in some of these diseases in which the underlying genetic defect is currently undefined.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Chromosomal single-strand breaks are amongst the commonest lesions arising in cells (thousands per cell/per day) and the repair of these breaks is critical for maintenance for genetic integrity. However, the importance of a proper cellular response to, and repair of, these lesions to human health is currently unclear. Here, we provide preliminary evidence that loss of this cellular single-strand break repair capacity accounts for the recessive neurodegenerative disease, spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy-1 (SCAN1). In the proposed work, we plan to address this hypothesis in detail and examine whether similar defects can account for other cases of, as yet genetically undefined, spinocerebellar ataxia.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2005-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>189321</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr